<m1>H<m2><ql>
<m0>e's Dr. Dad. His TV parenting programs and columns for Parents magazine and The New York Times have made him a household name.<ep>
  ``What I do,'' Lawrence Kutner explains, ``I can't quite describe.'' Then he does: ``I try to help parents get inside their children's heads.''<ep>
   He'll bring that philosophy with him Sunday as the keynote speaker at the Second Annual Parenting Conference at the Alper Jewish Community Center in Kendall. He'll also bring his new book, <m0>Your School-Age Child <m0>(William Morrow & Co., $20), the third entry in his four-part Parent & Child series. The book, writes Publishers Weekly, ``places him in the pantheon occupied by Spock, Brazelton and Leach.''<ep>
   In his talks and in his writing, Kutner, 44, and father of a 6-year-old son, deals with a myriad of issues: from parents' frustrations to the reasons behind sibling rivalry and why a fear of monsters under the bed is a good sign. By using lots of anecdotes and simple advice (--) give the child a spray bottle against monsters (--) he navigates tough terrain. He believes a good parent must, above all, be educated to understand <m0>why<m0> a child behaves the way he does.<ep>
  ``The parents who are the most frustrated, the most overwhelmed are the ones who don't understand the normal development of childhood. It's much easier to deal with a child once you understand why he's doing what he's doing,'' he adds.<ep>
  Kutner's work is not a how-to manual. Rather, he offers parents an explanation <m2><ql>
<ql>
PLEASE SEE  FAMILY MATTERS,  2F<qr>
